title: No rust for Forks after forfeit wins
text:
No rust for Forks after forfeit wins 
By wbng sports October 25, 2015 Updated Oct 25, 2015 at 6:55 PM EDT 
Town of Chenango, NY (WBNG Binghamton) In the NFL, a bye week typically gives players a chance to rest, spend time with their families and, in general, just plain relax. 
However, when you play just one game in three weeks thanks to forfeits like Chenango Forks did, you start to wonder if you'll be a bit rusty. 
After seeing his team play a grand total of four quarters in three weeks, head coach Dave Hogan thought his Blue Devils would have to shake off some rust against rival Chenango Valley. 
Nope. 
By halftime, Forks (7-1) had jumped out to a commanding 29-7 lead and never looked back, winning 43-27 to beat the Warriors for a 22nd consecutive time. 
"We talked about we'd probably have some rust to start with, but I'm not sure how much rust we did have," Hogan said. "Our defense played very well and certainly up front we played very well, too." 
"Everyone came out, they were ready to play, they were hyper," said Forks quarterback LJ Watson. "Everybody wanted the ball, we were making our blocks. We got a few calls that were put against us, but that didn't stop us from doing what we had to do." 
Chenango Forks, the top-ranked Class C team in New York, plays Dryden (5-3) in the Section IV semifinals on Saturday, Oct. 31 at Union-Endicott.
